# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 142nd-ioc-session
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:142nd-ioc-session/117th-ioc-session] The **117th International Olympic Committee Session** was held for the first time in Singapore from 2 to 9 July 2005.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/117th-ioc-session] Two important decisions were made through voting during the session – namely the selection of the hosting city for the 2012 Summer Olympics, and a review of the 28 sports currently represented in the summer games.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/117th-ioc-session] The session was held at the Raffles City Convention Centre, which is on level 4 of the Raffles City complex.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/117th-ioc-session] The opening ceremony on 5 July 2005 was held at the Esplanade – Theatres on the Bay.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/117th-ioc-session] An exhibition was launched at the podium of the Raffles City Shopping Complex, that would continue until 10 July.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/117th-ioc-session] The IOC's executive board started two days of meetings.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/117th-ioc-session] The executive board meetings resumed with updates on the progress of preparations for the 2006 Winter Olympics in Turin, 2008 Summer Olympics in Beijing and 2010 Winter Olympics in Vancouver by their respective representatives.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/117th-ioc-session] The board approved Beijing's request to hold the equestrian events in Hong Kong, which is a separate NOC from mainland China in the "best interests of the competition and the well-being of the horses".
[src:142nd-ioc-session/117th-ioc-session] The opening ceremony was held at the Esplanade - Theatres on the Bay and the guest of honour was the Prime Minister of Singapore, Lee Hsien Loong, who officially opened the session.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/117th-ioc-session] A special type of hybrid orchid had been bred to commemorate the IOC Session in Singapore.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/117th-ioc-session] A cultural performance of dance and songs was held with the theme of "One Voice, One Rhythm, One World".
[src:142nd-ioc-session/117th-ioc-session] Each of the five bid cities had 45 minutes to make a final presentation to the IOC members, after which voting commenced and the final results were announced at 19:30 Singapore time.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/117th-ioc-session] The final evaluation report of the 2004 Summer Olympics in Athens was presented and the Athens Games were finally closed.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/117th-ioc-session] Reports on the progress of preparations for future Games were also submitted.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/117th-ioc-session] The 28 sports in the Summer Olympics programme that existed at that time were all put up on the ballots, three years after a similar attempt failed to gain support from IOC members during the 114th IOC Session in Mexico City.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/117th-ioc-session] Prior to the voting, baseball, softball, modern pentathlon, taekwondo and fencing were considered as most likely to be dropped.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/117th-ioc-session] Five non-Olympic sports would then be voted to get in, in case any of the existing sports would be dropped, as IOC rules allow a maximum of 28 Summer Olympic sports.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/117th-ioc-session] These sports – golf, roller sports, squash, rugby and karate – were recommended by the IOC Olympic Games Program Committee, which has shortlisted the sports that applied to be included.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/117th-ioc-session] Golf and rugby were considered the favorites to be voted in, both mainly for their popularity and also for their relatively small number of events (each one, if accepted, would have consisted of 2 events).
[src:142nd-ioc-session/117th-ioc-session] A few days before the votes were cast, the IOC accepted the ASOIF request that the number of votes given for each sport will not be published, only "yay" or "nay".
[src:142nd-ioc-session/117th-ioc-session] The reason given for the unusual request was in order to avoid a "popularity ranking" of all Olympic sports.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/117th-ioc-session] Any sport that would get a simple majority of "nay" would be dropped from the Olympic program in 2012, but would remain eligible for readmission in future Games.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/117th-ioc-session] In the morning IOC members voted to remove baseball and softball from the games.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/117th-ioc-session] The decision has triggered dismay in some nations such as the United States where both sports originated from, and Canada, where both have a strong following.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/117th-ioc-session] The main reason for exclusion of softball was that it was included as a women-only sport mainly to be a gender-equalizer bat-and-ball sport for baseball (men-only sport), and with baseball out this reasoning no longer existed.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/117th-ioc-session] Another reason given was that both sports consist of large teams and their elimination will make room for many athletes, in comparison to modern pentathlon, for example, which only consist of 64 athletes.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/117th-ioc-session] In the afternoon, a secret vote by IOC members gave squash and karate over 51% of votes, but a subsequent vote to include them in the list of Olympic sports in the Olympic Charter has failed to get the necessary two-thirds majority needed for such amendment.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/117th-ioc-session] Therefore, by the end of the day two sports were dropped and none added, and the program of the 2012 Summer Olympics was reduced to 26 sports.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/117th-ioc-session] That night at The Oriental Singapore, then SNOC president and defence minister, Teo Chee Hean threw a banquet.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/117th-ioc-session] Rogge gave Singapore full marks for the session organisation, a perfect 6.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/117th-ioc-session] Lambis Nikolaou of Greece and Chiharu Igaya from Japan were elected as Vice presidents.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/117th-ioc-session] Singapore's IOC member, Ng Ser Miang was elected to the IOC Executive Board to replace Nikolaou, whose term as board member was due to expire.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/117th-ioc-session] The trio who sung the Olympic Hymn in Greek was criticised by both the media and the audience.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/117th-ioc-session] They were Singaporean soprano Khor Ai Ming, Singaporean tenor William Lim and Japanese soprano Satsuki Nagatome.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/117th-ioc-session] The trio sung with gusto just before the announcement of the 2012 Summer Olympics.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/121st-ioc-session] The **121st International Olympic Committee (IOC) Session** was held on 1–9 October 2009 in Copenhagen, Denmark, during which Rio de Janeiro was selected as the host city of the 2016 Summer Olympics.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/121st-ioc-session] The city of Copenhagen was chosen on 8 February 2006 by the 118th IOC Session held in Turin, Italy to stage the 13th Olympic Congress, together with the meetings of the Executive Board and the 121st IOC Session.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/121st-ioc-session] The other candidates were Athens (Greece), Busan (South Korea), Cairo (Egypt), Riga (Latvia), Singapore, Taipei (Chinese Taipei).
[src:142nd-ioc-session/121st-ioc-session] Convened on the initiative of President Jacques Rogge, the 13th Olympic Congress brought together all the constituent parties of the Olympic Movement to study and discuss the current functioning of the Movement and define the main development axes for the future.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/121st-ioc-session] On 2 October 2009, the IOC voted to elect the host city of the 2016 Summer Olympics.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/121st-ioc-session] Rio de Janeiro was elected host city after three rounds of voting.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/121st-ioc-session] This was Rio's fourth bid for the Olympic Games.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/121st-ioc-session] In 2017, Brazilian police and prosecutors investigated allegations that the Rio 2016 bidding process had involved vote-buying.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/121st-ioc-session] The investigation focused on claims that Carlos Arthur Nuzman, then president of the Brazilian Olympic Committee and head of the Rio 2016 bid committee, helped arrang a US$2 million payment connected to Lamine Diack and Papa Massata Diack shortly before Rio was selected as host city.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/121st-ioc-session] In 2019, former Rio de Janeiro governor Sérgio Cabral testified that he had paid US$2 million in bribes to secure votes for Rio's bid, allegations that led the IOC to open an inquiry.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/121st-ioc-session] In 2024, a Brazilian federal court annulled corruption convictions related to the Rio selection, ruling that the judge who had issued the convictions lacked legal competence in the case.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/121st-ioc-session] On 9 October 2009, Jacques Rogge was re-elected as IOC president for a final four-year term.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/121st-ioc-session] He was the only candidate and was re-elected by a vote of 88-1, with three abstentions.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/121st-ioc-session] The session also elected Mario Pescante and Ng Ser Miang as IOC vice-presidents, and Craig Reedie and John Coates to the IOC Executive Board.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/121st-ioc-session] Six new IOC members were elected: Richard Peterkin, Crown Prince Frederik of Denmark, Habu Ahmed Gumel, Habib Abdul Nabi Macki, Lydia Nsekera, and Göran Petersson.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/121st-ioc-session] The Session decided to add Rugby Sevens and Golf to the Rio 2016 program.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/121st-ioc-session] The tally for rugby was 81 in favor, with 8 against, and golf was approved 63–26.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/121st-ioc-session] Neither sport is new to the Olympics — rugby was last featured at the Olympics in 1924, and golf in 1904.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/123rd-ioc-session] The **123rd International Olympic Committee Session** (or the **2011 International Olympic Committee Session**, the **123rd IOC Session** or the **2011 IOC Session**) was held in July 2011 at the Inkosi Albert Luthuli International Convention Centre in Durban, South Africa.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/123rd-ioc-session] At the session, Pyeongchang, South Korea was announced as the host city of the 2018 Olympic Winter Games and Paralympic Winter Games.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/123rd-ioc-session] The International Olympic Committee officially announced Durban as the host city of the 123rd IOC Session at the 120th IOC Session in Beijing, People's Republic of China on 7 August 2008, before the 2008 Summer Olympics.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/123rd-ioc-session] IOC withdrew recognition of the NOC of the Netherlands Antilles following the formal dissolution of Netherlands Antilles on 10 October 2010.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/123rd-ioc-session] The athletes of the five islands comprising the Netherlands Antilles were allowed to qualify and compete in the 2012 Olympic Games as independent athletes under the Olympic flag.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/123rd-ioc-session] The sport of floorball was granted full IOC recognition.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/125th-ioc-session] The **125th IOC Session** took place at the Buenos Aires Hilton in Buenos Aires, Argentina, from 7 to 10 September 2013.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/125th-ioc-session] On 7 September, the International Olympic Committee (IOC) elected Tokyo as the host city of the 2020 Summer Olympic Games.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/125th-ioc-session] Wrestling was restored to the Olympic sports program for 2020 and 2024.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/125th-ioc-session] Thomas Bach was elected to an eight-year term as IOC President on 10 September.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/125th-ioc-session] The IOC received bids from two cities to host the 125th Session: the Argentine capital Buenos Aires and the Malaysian capital Kuala Lumpur made bids.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/125th-ioc-session] Buenos Aires was elected at the 122nd IOC Session in Vancouver which took place prior to the 2010 Winter Olympics.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/125th-ioc-session] The members of the IOC elected the host city of the 2020 Olympic Games on 7 September 2013.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/125th-ioc-session] The candidates were Tokyo, Istanbul, and Madrid.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/125th-ioc-session] Prior to the vote, the contest was considered to be close between the three cities.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/125th-ioc-session] Tokyo was awarded the 2020 Summer Olympics.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/125th-ioc-session] Following Madrid's elimination after a tie-breaking vote with Istanbul, the three Spanish IOC members were eligible to take part in the final round of voting.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/125th-ioc-session] The announcement was met with jubilation from the Tokyo delegation and across Japan.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/125th-ioc-session] Abe's role in the final stages of the bid, including his reassurances to the IOC that Fukushima radiation would not affect Tokyo, was considered to be a major asset.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/125th-ioc-session] Tokyo's bid had also received support from Princess Hisako and Sheikh Ahmad Al-Fahad Al-Sabah.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/125th-ioc-session] Madrid's bid was considered to have been hampered by Spain's weak economy and Istanbul's was considered to have been damaged by recent internal political instability and doping scandals, as well as match fixing in 2011.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/125th-ioc-session] After Tokyo was selected as host city, the bidding process became the subject of investigations in France concerning payments made by the Tokyo bid committee to Black Tidings, a Singapore-based consultancy.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/125th-ioc-session] Reuters reported that Tokyo bid president Tsunekazu Takeda approved a payment of nearly US$1 million to Black Tidings shortly before the 2013 host-city vote, and that Dentsu, an IOC marketing partner, had supported Tokyo's bid campaign.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/125th-ioc-session] The Tokyo 2020 organising structure was later affected by separate bribery and bid-rigging investigations.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/125th-ioc-session] Former Tokyo 2020 executive board member Haruyuki Takahashi, a former senior executive at Dentsu, was accused of receiving payments from companies in connection with Olympic sponsorship and licensing contracts.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/125th-ioc-session] In 2023, Japanese prosecutors indicated Dentsu, Hakuhodo and other companies over alleged bid-rigging related to Tokyo Olympic contracts.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/125th-ioc-session] On 10 September 2013, Thomas Bach of Germany was elected to succeed Jacques Rogge as IOC President, winning in two rounds of voting, over five other candidates.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/125th-ioc-session] King Willem-Alexander of the Netherlands was awarded this highest IOC honor on Sunday 8 September after he relinquished his membership to focus on matters at home.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/125th-ioc-session] The IOC considered wrestling, squash and baseball/softball to the program for the 2020 Summer Olympics.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/125th-ioc-session] Wrestling had been part of the Ancient Olympic Games and every Modern Olympic Games with the exception of the 1900 Paris Games, however in February 2013 it was dropped from the 2020 Olympic Program.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/125th-ioc-session] Wrestling successfully campaigned at the 125th Session to be re-included in the 2020 program.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/125th-ioc-session] Baseball was first included as a demonstration sport at the 1904 Summer Olympics in St.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/125th-ioc-session] It was again played as a demonstration sport at the Summer Olympics in 1912, 1936, 1956, 1964, 1984, and 1988.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/125th-ioc-session] It was first included as an official medal sport at the 1992 Summer Olympics in Barcelona.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/125th-ioc-session] Baseball then featured at every Summer Olympic Games until the 2008 Olympics in Beijing, where it made its last Olympic appearance.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/125th-ioc-session] Softball was included at the Summer Olympics in 1996, 2000, 2004, and 2008.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/125th-ioc-session] The governing bodies for baseball (International Baseball Federation) and softball (International Softball Federation) merged in 2013 to form the World Baseball Softball Confederation.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/125th-ioc-session] The two sports each had a separate bid for joining the Olympic program.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/125th-ioc-session] Although Baseball and Softball were not successful in being included in the 2020 Olympic core program, in 2016 the Tokyo Olympic Organizing Committee and the WBSC successfully campaigned to have the two sports included in the 2020 Games as a one sport, two discipline event for a one-off appearance.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/125th-ioc-session] Squash is played in more than 185 countries and by millions of people worldwide.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/125th-ioc-session] It has been played at various international sporting events, including the Pan American Games since 1995, and the All-Africa Games since 2003.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/125th-ioc-session] Squash has also been played at both the Commonwealth Games and the Asian Games since 1998.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/125th-ioc-session] The sport is governed by the World Squash Federation.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/125th-ioc-session] Wrestling is practiced all around the world, officially in 177 countries, some of which participate in the Olympic Games in this sport alone.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/125th-ioc-session] It was first introduced in the ancient Olympic Games in 708 BC and was included in all the ancient Olympics from that date.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/125th-ioc-session] Wrestling has featured at the modern Summer Games since the 1896 Olympics in Athens, and it has been a part of all modern Olympics except those in Paris in 1900.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/125th-ioc-session] It was still included in the Olympic program at the 2016 Summer Olympics in Rio de Janeiro.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/125th-ioc-session] Wrestling was initially dropped from the 2020 Olympic program; however, it was given the opportunity to be reselected for the 2020 and 2024 Games.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/125th-ioc-session] The sport is governed by United World Wrestling.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/127th-ioc-session] The **127th IOC Session** took place in December 2014 in Monte Carlo, Monaco.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/127th-ioc-session] All provisions in the Olympic Agenda 2020 reform package were approved by the full IOC membership.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/127th-ioc-session] On December 9, 2014, the IOC members voted for the 131st IOC Session host city in 2017.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/127th-ioc-session] The IOC approved Kosovo's inclusion as a full member of the Committee, allowing the country to participate in Rio 2016 under its national flag and the IOC code of **KOS**.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/128th-ioc-session] The **128th IOC Session** took place from July 31 – August 3, 2015, in Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia at the Kuala Lumpur Convention Centre.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/128th-ioc-session] The host city for the 2022 Winter Olympics and the 2020 Winter Youth Olympics were elected during the 128th IOC Session on July 31, 2015.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/128th-ioc-session] Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia and Lima, Peru placed bids to host the 128th IOC Session.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/128th-ioc-session] Kuala Lumpur bid to host the 125th IOC Session which took place in 2013, but they lost out to Buenos Aires.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/128th-ioc-session] Lima's bid to host the IOC Session was ruled out by the evaluation report which resulted in Kuala Lumpur becoming the host city.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/128th-ioc-session] Lima later hosted the 131st IOC Session two years after Kuala Lumpur hosted the meeting.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/128th-ioc-session] The host city of the 2022 Winter Olympics was elected during the 128th IOC Session.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/128th-ioc-session] Bids for the games were due to the IOC in 2013.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/128th-ioc-session] In 2014, the IOC decided that Almaty and Beijing (as Oslo withdrew its bid), would become candidate cities, a year before the host city was elected.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/128th-ioc-session] The host city of the 2020 Winter Youth Olympics was also chosen during the same IOC session.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/128th-ioc-session] The two candidate cities, Lausanne, Switzerland, and Brașov, Romania, were shortlisted in early December.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/128th-ioc-session] Participants of session have considered the sports to be added to the Tokyo 2020 program.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/128th-ioc-session] A new shortlist of eight sports were unveiled on June 22, 2015.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/128th-ioc-session] These sports include baseball/softball, bowling, karate, roller sports, sport climbing, squash, surfing, and wushu.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/128th-ioc-session] The federations of the eight sports made their presentations in Tokyo on August 7–8, 2015.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/128th-ioc-session] In September 2015, organisers will recommend one or more of the sports to the International Olympic Committee for inclusion in 2020 Olympic program, with the final decision in August 2016.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/128th-ioc-session] The IOC approved South Sudan's inclusion as a full member of the Committee, allowed the country to participate in Rio 2016 under its national flag.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/128th-ioc-session] The IOC code for South Sudan Olympic Team is **SSD**.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/129th-ioc-session] The 129th Session of the International Olympic Committee, was held in Rio de Janeiro, Brazil from August 1 to August 4, 2016, prior to the Games of the XXXI Olympiad, being held in Rio.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/129th-ioc-session] Some key moments of the session included a keynote address from Professor Muhammad Yunus and the election of new sports for the 2020 Olympic program.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/129th-ioc-session] After the introduction of Olympic Agenda 2020 in 2014, the IOC granted Olympic host city organizing committees the ability to propose other sports in addition to the core olympic sports to be included in their respective Olympic Games.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/129th-ioc-session] Several International Sports Federations campaigned to the Tokyo Organizing Committee to be included in the 2020 program; eventually the Tokyo OCOG made the decision to propose the inclusion of baseball/softball(as one sport, two disciplines), karate, skateboarding, sport climbing and surfing.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/129th-ioc-session] The 2020 organizing committee presented the five sport package to the full International Olympic Committee at the IOC session in Rio on August 3, 2016.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/129th-ioc-session] The IOC, unanimously approved the proposal of the inclusion of the five sports for a one-off appearance in the Tokyo Games.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/142nd-ioc-session] The **142nd IOC Session** was an IOC Session that was held in Paris, France from 22 to 24 July and resumed for a single day on 10 August 2024, as part of the 2024 Summer Olympics.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/142nd-ioc-session] Meeting at the Palais des Congrès de Paris at the Porte Maillot for the rest of the session, the IOC voted for the Olympic Esports Series to be replaced by the Olympic Esports Games, with the first edition being held in Saudi Arabia in 2025.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/142nd-ioc-session] The IOC also received updates on the Olympic AI Agenda, noting over 180 potential use cases for AI across the Olympic Movement.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/142nd-ioc-session] Both the 2030 and the 2034 Winter Olympics hosts were awarded at the session, with the French Alps and Salt Lake City each starting with their respective bid presentations, followed by a report from Karl Stoss, IOC Member and Chair of the Future Host City Commission of the Olympic Winter Games.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/142nd-ioc-session] Afterwards, the IOC proceeded with the voting on whether the committee accepted the French Alps and Salt Lake City, Utah as hosts of the 2030 and 2034 Winter Olympics, respectively.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/142nd-ioc-session] The French bid was a latecomer in the competition to host, going into "targeted dialogue" with the IOC in late November 2023, only four months after declaring its intention to host the previous July.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/142nd-ioc-session] In contravention of the Olympic Charter, with the French Alps being chosen while the session was held in France, this became the first instance in which a candidate city had been chosen in the same country, the last time occurring in 1939 for the 1944 Olympic Games when no such prohibition existed.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/142nd-ioc-session] The year previous, a delay to 2025 was speculated by the media.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/142nd-ioc-session] The French bid also lacked financial commitment from the national and regional governments, which made host city election conditional on those guarantees.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/142nd-ioc-session] This person in turn would be the signer when instructed by the president, with a deadline for 1 October 2024 set by the IOC.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/142nd-ioc-session] The French National Assembly would have to ratify it by 1 March 2025 to satisfy the IOC's conditions.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/142nd-ioc-session] The American bid had previously signed an agreement which entailed that the organizers and Utah politicians would lobby the federal government to overturn Rodchenkov Act, named for Grigory Rodchenkov.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/142nd-ioc-session] The law permitted the federal government wide jurisdiction in doping enforcement worldwide, following the World Anti-Doping Agency's declaration that 23 Chinese swimmers who failed drug tests could compete in the 2020 Summer Olympics.
[src:142nd-ioc-session/142nd-ioc-session] Indian Olympic shooter Abhinav Bindra was presented with the Olympic Order which was awarded to him on 23 July.
